fields.title: Installing Django
fields.overview: Here we will be setting up our django project with the idea of hosting it on AWS Free tier. Therefore settings will be in two parts called "production" and "development". We will also talk about setting up secure environmental variable in our project. So lets get into it.
fields.content:
Installing Python

First, we need to install Python on our machine.

On Ubuntu

Python is already installed on your machine. To check the python version run 

python3 --version

On your terminal. I will be using the python 3.10 version for this tutorial series. As it is the latest version while making this series. 

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get upgrade

Run the above commands to update and upgrade the outdated packages in your system.

On Windows

Download the latest python version that is available from here

Make sure to check the add to PATH checkbox while installing. 

Installing Django

First check the Django versions that support your version of python, here. I will use Django v4.1 throughout this series as it is the latest version. You can go with the latest LTS version or the latest update.

Creating a virtual environment

A virtual environment is an isolated container for your specific project. Basically, the packages you install using pip will be installed in this container rather than in your primary operating system. Learn more about virtual environments. First, create a folder for your project. Then open your project folder using a preferred terminal.

cd <path to your folder>

Then we will use python's venv package to create the virtual environment for our project.

python3 -m venv env

You will see a new folder created inside your project folder called "env". This will be the isolated environment of our project. After creating the virtual env, we need to activate it.

For Ubuntu
source env/bin/activate
For Windows
source ./env/Scripts/activate

Installing Django

After successfully activating your virtual env. Enter the following in the console.

python3 -m pip install Django

Now you will see that python-pip is installing all the packages that are needed to run Django on your machine. In addition to this I recommend installing Pillow.

python3 -m pip install --upgrade pip
python3 -m pip install --upgrade Pillow

 Run the following to create the Django project. Add the last period to make the project in the same folder you are working on.

django-admin startproject core .

Congrats now you have successfully created a Django project on your machine. You can run the project using 

python3 manage.py runserver

and go to 127.0.0.1:8000/ in your browser.

Next, we will look at "Environmental Variables" of our project

fields.title: Environmental Variables
fields.overview: Here we will be talking about setting up the production and development settings of the project. Also, we will talk about setting up the secrets and environmental variables for the project.
fields.content:
Previously we talked about Installing Django.

Setting up environment variables with decouple

Python-decouple is a library that helps you separate the settings parameters from your source code. It's helpful if you push your code to a remote repository. To GitHub or GitLab for example. You can hide your sensitive info from the public. View more information about the package here.

Install python-decouple

python3 -m pip install python-decouple

Setting up the Env file

Create a new file and name it .env on the project root folder where the manage.py file is. Make sure the file has no name and the file extension is .env

Adding .gitignore

If you are going to use git as the version control. Create a new file on your project root folder and rename it .gitignore. And add the following lines and save the file. 

.env
env/

 This will ignore the environment variables file and the virtual environment files from being added to the git repository.

Setting up settings.py

First, create a new folder inside your core folder called settings. Then move the settings.py folder inside the settings folder and rename the settings.py file to base.py

Now create three more files inside the settings folder and name them __init__.py, production.py, and development.py. Now your project folder structure should look something like below.

📂 core

📂 settings

🗎 __init__.py

🗎 base.py

🗎 development.py

🗎 production.py

🗎 __init__.py

🗎 asgi.py

🗎 urls.py

🗎 wsgi.py

📁 env

🗎 db.sqlite3

🗎 manage.py

Setting up the project for development

First, let us configure the base.py file. Open the base.py file with your favorite text editor. Now add the following line and import the decouple package.

from decouple import config

Now search for the BASE_DIR variable and add another .parent at the end. Now it should look something like this

BASE_DIR = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent.parent

Then change DEBUG variable to

DEBUG = config('DEBUG', default=True, cast=bool)

Then add the following line inside the .env file

DEBUG = True

Import the base file into the development and production files by adding 

from .base import *

to both the .py files. Now select the following variables and move them into both production and development files.

SECRET_KEY = <Some random large string containing numbers and characters>
ALLOWED_HOSTS = []

We will add more variables to these files as we go further into our project.

Next, open the manage.py file in the project root folder and the wsgi.py, and asgi.py in the core folder. Next, search for the following line in these 3 files

os.environ.setdefault('DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE', 'core.settings')

 and replace it with

DEBUG = config('DEBUG', default=True, cast=bool)
if DEBUG:
    os.environ.setdefault('DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE', 'core.settings.development')
else:
    os.environ.setdefault('DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE', 'core.settings.production')

and don't forget to import the decouple package in these files as well.

from decouple import config

Now you can switch the project between production settings and development settings by changing the DEBUG value of the .env file. Read more about DEBUG variable of the settings.py from here.

Furthermore, we can set up our development.py file to allow all hosts by

ALLOWED_HOSTS = ['*']

and our production.py file to only allow our specified hosts like

ALLOWED_HOSTS = ['www.example.com', 'example.com']

While this is totally fine I prefer to include the allowed hosts in the .env file as well. To do this in the production.py file, I am going to change ALLOWED_HOSTS to get the value from environment variables

ALLOWED_HOSTS = config('ALLOWED_HOSTS', cast=list)

and then add a new entry to the .env file

ALLOWED_HOSTS = ['www.example.com', 'example.com']

One more thing, add a secure SECRET_KEY to your production settings. To generate a new key visit here. Now to test your newly learned skills add it to the .env file and import the key to your production settings. Tip - Add cast as a good practice when you import the environment variables. Good luck!

And now our setup is complete. We now have production and development-ready Django project. Not exactly but we are close xD

fields.title: Scapegoat
fields.description:
[ˈskeɪpɡəʊt]
NOUN
a person who is blamed for the wrongdoings, mistakes, or faults of others, especially for reasons of expediency.
synonyms:
whipping boy · victim · Aunt Sally · goat
(in the Bible) a goat sent into the wilderness after the Jewish chief priest had symbolically laid the sins of the people upon it (Lev. 16).
